#: ../../Ch04/Ch04_Descriptives_1.rst:344
msgid ""
"One last point to make regarding the mode. Whilst the mode is most often "
"calculated when you have nominal data, because means and medians are "
"useless for those sorts of variables, there are some situations in which "
"you really do want to know the mode of an ordinal, interval or ratio "
"scale variable. For instance, let’s go back to our ``afl.margins`` "
"variable. This variable is clearly ratio scale (if it’s not clear to you,"
" it may help to re-read section :doc:`Scales of measurement "
"<../Ch02/Ch02_StudyDesign_2>`), and so in most situations the mean or the"
" median is the measure of central tendency that you want. But consider "
"this scenario: a friend of yours is offering a bet and they pick a "
